{
  "query": "What are the typical effects of rewetting on the vegetation of drained peatlands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 36 studies evaluating the effects of rewetting on peatland vegetation (Action 1756), typical effects include significant changes in plant community composition where drier grassland communities are replaced by more wetland- or peatland-characteristic communities. Rewetting typically increases Sphagnum moss cover or abundance in bogs, fens and other peatlands, with 12 studies reporting this effect. Herb cover shows consistent increases, particularly for sedges (13 of 15 studies showed increased sedge cover), cottongrass (8 of 9 studies), and reed/rush cover (5 of 7 studies). Tree and shrub cover typically reduces or shows no effect following rewetting, with 10 studies reporting these outcomes. Wetland-characteristic plants generally increase in abundance following rewetting, while upland plant cover decreases. Effects on overall plant species richness and diversity are mixed, with 6 studies showing increases and 5 studies showing no effect. For combined interventions of cutting/removing trees and rewetting (Action 1732), studies show increased cover of herbs including cottongrasses and sedges, increased Sphagnum cover in some cases, and changes in plant community composition to become less like drained forested sites. Multiple restoration interventions including rewetting (Action 1803) consistently increase total moss or bryophyte cover and herbaceous plant cover including cottongrass and other grass-like plants.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1756",
    "1732",
    "1803"
  ]
}

