{
  "query": "What are the known benefits and harms of adding lime or inorganic fertilizers to aid peatland vegetation establishment?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies of adding lime and inorganic fertilizers to peatland vegetation establishment, several benefits and harms have been documented. For inorganic fertilizers (Action 1826), benefits include increased survival of some planted tree species, typically increased growth of planted mosses, herbs or trees, and increased total vegetation, vascular plant and bryophyte cover in some studies. However, fertilizer had no effect on three planted tree species and reduced survival of one tree species in one study, had no effect on growth for some species or conditions, and typically had no effect on growth of peat swamp tree seedlings in nursery conditions. For lime application (Actions 1790 and 1825), benefits include increased overall vegetation biomass (mostly grass) in fen meadows, increased survival of planted fen mosses, increased growth of planted fen mosses, and increased cover of sown mosses in some studies. However, lime also showed harmful effects including typically reduced survival of planted fen herbs after two growing seasons, reduced or no effect on Sphagnum moss growth in bog pools, reduced growth rates for the majority of peat swamp tree seedlings in nursery conditions, and no effect on total vegetation, vascular plant or bryophyte cover in some studies. The effectiveness appears to depend on the specific species, chemical composition of treatments, peat preparation methods, and whether the system is being restored as a bog versus fen.",
